[[File:Kitano-Tenjin-sha sandō.jpg|thumb|At the southern approach of Kitano Tenjinsha]]
'''Kitano Tenjinsha''' (きたのてんじんじゃ) is a {{jalink|Shinto shrine|Q845945}} located in {{jalink|Saitama Prefecture|Q128186}}{{jalink|Tokorozawa City|Q165857}}{{jalink|Kotesashi Motomachi|Q11460790}}. It is a {{jalink|Engishiki Jinmyōchō|Q11064932|Shikinaisha}} (two proposed identifications, one {{jalink|disputed shrine|Q135022904}}), and under the {{jalink|modern system of shrine rankings|Q712534|former shrine ranking system}} it was classified as a {{jalink|prefectural shrine}}.

The registered {{jalink|corporate registry|Q83708009}} religious corporation name is '''Mononobe Tenjinsha / Kuniichi Chigi Jinja / Tenman Tenjinsha''', and “Kitano Tenjinsha” is the collective name for these shrines.<ref>{{Cite web|Japanese|url=http://www.city.tokorozawa.saitama.jp/iitokoro/enjoy/kids/shokai/meisyokyuseki/kitanotenjinsya.html |title=Kitano Tenjinsha (Kitano) |date=2008-10-31 |publisher=Tokorozawa City Board of Education, Cultural Properties Protection Division |accessdate=2015-06}}</ref>

=== Enshrined deities ===
* Mononobe Tenjinsha: {{jalink|Nigihayahi|Q10949054|Kushitama Nigihayahi-no-Mikoto}} – identified with the minor Shikinaisha “Mononobe Tenjinsha”; jointly enshrines {{jalink|Izumo Iwai Shrine (disambiguation)|Q104539298|Izumo Iwai Shrine}}.
* Kuniichi Chigi Jinja: {{jalink|Ōkuninushi|Q276944|Yachihoko-no-Kami}} – identified with the minor Shikinaisha “{{jalink|Kuniichi Chigi Shrine (disambiguation)||Kuniichi Chigi Shrine}}”.
* Tenman Tenjinsha: {{jalink|Sugawara no Michizane|Q382005}}

=== Jointly enshrined ===
* {{jalink|Prince Muneyoshi|Q541057}}
* Kotesashi Myōjin
* {{jalink|Ame-no-Hohi|Q10940685|Ame-no-Hohi-no-Mikoto}}
* {{jalink|Emperor Ōjin|Q317997}}
* {{jalink|Yamato Takeru|Q461258|Yamato Takeru-no-Mikoto}}
* {{jalink|Ukanomitama|Q3080728|Ukanomitama-no-Mikoto}}<ref name="Kitano Tenjinsha summary">Summary displayed in front of the shrine, Kitano Tenjinsha. Viewed January 15, 2022.</ref>

=== History ===
According to shrine tradition, it was founded when {{jalink|Yamato Takeru|Q461258}} established the shrine during his eastern campaign. During the {{jalink|Edo period|Q184963}}, it received a {{jalink|shuinjō|Q11093673}} from the {{jalink|Tokugawa shogunate|Q205662}}.
* Mononobe Tenjinsha was the {{jalink|ujigami|Q767655}} (clan tutelary deity) of the Mononobe clan (see {{jalink|Nashiki no Kuni no Miyatsuko#Clan|Q11504612}}). The ancestral deity {{jalink|Nigihayahi|Q10949054|Nigihayahi-no-Mikoto}} is still enshrined today.
* As a Tenjin shrine, in {{jalink|Chōtoku|Q1327213}} 1 ({{jalink|995|Q23794}}), {{jalink|Sugawara no Sukenari}}, a fifth-generation descendant of Sugawara no Michizane, invited the deity from Kyoto’s {{jalink|Kitano Tenmangū|Q662176|Kitano Shrine}} while serving as {{jalink|Governor of Musashi}}. Thereafter, shrine buildings were constructed by {{jalink|Minamoto no Yoshiie|Q32613}}, {{jalink|Minamoto no Yoritomo|Q242800}}, {{jalink|Ashikaga Takauji|Q297107}}, and {{jalink|Maeda Toshiie|Q1196817}}.
* Edo public exhibition – From April 1 to June 1, {{jalink|Kyōhō|Q1145048}} 7 ({{jalink|1722|Q6918}}), a public display of the shrine’s sacred object was held at the former {{jalink|Mejiro Fudō-in Hasedera|Q11646320}} in {{jalink|Edo|Q215646}}. During this period, on April 24, hanging scrolls and documents from the shrine treasury were submitted inside Edo Castle at the shogun’s request.<ref>{{Cite web|Japanese|url=https://www.asahi-net.or.jp/~hm9k-ajm/musasinorekisi/gosikifudoutomusasino/mejirofudou/kitanotennjinndekaityou/kitanotennjinnsyadekaityou.htm |title=Kitano Tenjinsha Edo Public Exhibition |work=Otamajakushi |date=2001-11-11 |publisher=Kiichi Ajima |accessdate=2015-06}}</ref>

=== Shrine grounds ===
Approaches lined with {{jalink|torii|Q234731}} gates and {{jalink|stone lanterns}} run along the western and southern sides of the grounds. The western side faces the former {{jalink|Kamakura Highway|Q2389309}}, which runs north–south, while from the south along {{jalink|Saitama Prefectural Route 179 / Tokyo Metropolitan Route 179|Q11427110}} one reaches the worship hall via multiple {{jalink|stairways|Q12511}} and torii gates.
; Subsidiary shrines
* Inari Shrine
* Yakumo Shrine
* {{jalink|Aviation Shrine (Tokorozawa)|Q124483190}} – Founded on September 25, {{jalink|1937|Q24666}} at {{jalink|Tokorozawa Army Airfield|Q11658682}} at the wish of {{jalink|Tokugawa Yoshitoshi|Q5694703}}. It was established to enshrine the spirits of fallen aviation personnel who had devoted their lives to the development of national aviation but were not enshrined at Yasukuni Shrine. In 1938, with the founding of the {{jalink|Army Aviation School|Q2822344}}, it was transferred from Tokorozawa to Toyooka (present-day {{jalink|Iruma Air Base|Q3015843}}). On September 3, 1945, before the site was requisitioned by U.S. forces, it was relocated to the grounds of this shrine.
* {{jalink|Ayako Tenmangū|Q17191862|Ayako Tenjinsha}} – Enshrines {{jalink|Tajihi no Ayako}}, the {{jalink|wet nurse|Q472898}} of {{jalink|Sugawara no Michizane|Q382005}}.
* Kotesashi Shrine – Enshrines the war dead (heroic spirits) of the Kotesashi area.
