; Trees on the grounds
* Mikoto-zakura – A {{jalink|cherry tree|Q19939}} said to have been planted by {{jalink|Yamato Takeru|Q461258}} in front of the shrine; it has repeatedly died and regenerated through {{jalink|suckers|Q960522}}.
* Dainagon Plum – Planted by {{jalink|Maeda Toshiie|Q1196817}} in {{jalink|Tenshō|Q1145058}} 18 ({{jalink|1590|Q6764}}); the current tree (as of 2015) is the second generation. Claiming descent from Sugawara no Michizane and using the {{jalink|plum crest}}, Maeda Toshiie is said to have stopped at the then-dilapidated shrine during the {{jalink|Odawara Campaign|Q2622890}} and rebuilt the shrine buildings, planting a single plum tree. The name derives from his court rank of {{jalink|Dainagon|Q1354706}} at the time.
; Other features
* Kitano Place-Name Origin Monument – A stone monument erected on September 25, {{jalink|Heisei|Q234510}} 18 ({{jalink|2006|Q2021}}), recording that although recent land readjustment changed the shrine’s address to Kotesashi Motomachi, the surrounding place-name “Kitano” derives from this shrine.
* {{jalink|Prince Muneyoshi|Q541057}} encampment site
* {{jalink|Temizuya}} – Rebuilt in recent years ({{jalink|2010s|Q19022}}), with a {{jalink|dragon|Q11675}} {{jalink|ceiling painting}}.
* Kagura hall
* {{jalink|Chikaraishi|Q1660393}}
* {{jalink|Sacred horse|Q11591047}} (shinme)
